<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>PARLIAMENTARY INQUIRY ON THE CODE FOR SUSTAINABLE HOMES AND THE HOUSING STANDARDS REVIEW – COMMENTS SUBMITTED BY WIENERBERGER LTD WITH RESPECT TO “MATERIALS” ASPECTS</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Wienerberger</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> Ltd</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">INTRODUCTION</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wienerberger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Ltd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who manufacture building products</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are concerned at the possible unintended consequences of the current Review of Housing Standards</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and proposed changes to the Code for Sustainable Homes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Whilst there is general agreement across the construction sector that streamlining and simplification of Building Regulations and associated documents (such as the Code for Sustainable Homes) will be extremely helpful to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">housebuilding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> sector, there are concerns that total abolition of any standards related to “Materials” in this review could lead to downgrading of the considerable work done in recent years to improve the Responsible Sourcing of construction products and could stifle innovation in the drive towards low carbon sustainable housing.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The removal of any material related standards could lead to inclusion in new housing of products with a much reduced service life and inferior technical properties which may prove to be expensive to rectify in the longer term. Other issues could be impaired indoor air quality and the creation of less healthy buildings. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wienerberger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Ltd</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> support the “Fabric First” principles e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">stablished</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the Code for Sustainable Homes and amplified in the proposed Fabric Energy Efficiency Standards (FEES).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wienerberger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Ltd also support the move towards development of harmonised systems for the provision of information on the environmental impacts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">of building materials </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">using</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Environmental Product Declarations (EPD) in accordance with BS EN 15804.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">DETAILED COMMENTS</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wienerberger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Ltd </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">recognise and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fully support the need for simplification and rationalisation of the multiplicity of Regulations and Codes applicable to UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ousebuilding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We do not support the retention of the Code for Sustainable Homes in its current form – not least because it does not give sufficient weight to the importance of “Materials” and “Fabric First</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. The Code currently contains some issues of peripheral importance which are assigned a higher priority than the fundamental aspects of the fabric of the house and its anticipated service life.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> we are concerned at the current indications that the “Materials” aspects of the Code will be completely removed and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it will be left to the market to establish </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">relevant standards. Among other aspects this is likely to create a plethora of different standards in different areas. This is totally contrary to the progression towards harmonised standards by the development of Environmental Product Declarations (EPD) in accordance with BS EN 15804.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It cannot be in the interests of any Stakeholders to have different materials standards in different regions of the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the Housing Standards Review it is essential that sufficient weight is given to the requirements for “Fabric First” and the “Materials” aspects of the construction products used in house walls.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Standards should be developed which are used uniformly across all regions of the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We suggest that the “Fabric First” approach is a more reliable route to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> sustained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> long term and cost effective energy and carbon savings from new housing when compared against complex “add on” heating and ventilation systems which require regular maintenance/replacement and which require constant attention and intervention by the house owner.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> This should be fully recognised in the Housing Standards Review.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">“Heavyweight” construction materials such as c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lay bricks and clay blocks have a significant role to play in “Fabric First” in relation to forming part of cost effective walling solutions which meet the “Fabric Energy Efficiency Standards”.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Clay bricks and clay blocks </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">offer an effective service life in excess of 150 years with minimal requirement for maintenance. This is important when house owners are looking at their house as a “lifetime investment” and is also important when seeking relevant finance and insurance cover.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> It is essential that the Housing Standards Review gives appropriate weight to the use of products with a long and proven service life.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Clay bricks and clay blocks offer the benefits of Thermal Mass in house walls which, in the longer term, will be important to avoid over heating without the need for expensive forced ventilation.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Clay bricks and blocks are a proven construction material which are well suited to achievement of the levels of airtightness necessary to meet the higher levels of the existing Code for Sustainable Homes. Houses built using clay masonry products are likely to achieve more predictable thermal performance in practice which is close to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the design performance. It is well known that some other construction methods can have a greater</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">performance gap” between design performance and achieved performance. This aspect needs to be fully considered in the Housing Standards Review</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Clay bricks and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">clay </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">blocks provide a completely inert and non toxic walling material which contribute to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> high standards of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> indoor air quality and therefore “Healthy” buildings. It is essential that the Housing Standards Review includes requirements for good indoor air quality and healthy ho</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">es.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Clay bricks and clay blocks have a long service life which can continue even beyond the life of the building they initially form part of.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> These flexible and durable products are easier to recycle and re use when compared to more modern “composite” materials. Aspects of “design for re use” need to be incorporated in any review of Housing standards.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Code for Sustainable Homes makes an important contribution towards increasing the standards for “Responsible Sourcing” of construction products. The UK clay brick manufacturing sector is fully committed to BES 6001 or equivalent schemes. It is important that aspects of Responsible Sourcing are maintained in the Housing Standards Review</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> even if the Code for Sustainable Homes is modified or withdrawn</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Without this, the likelihood of inferior quality products being imported from outside the European Union will rise with consequent risks to long term performance of new housing.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">CONCLUSIONS</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We fully support the view that the various documents and Codes related to Building Regulations should be consolidated and simplified but we feel that in doing this the standards related to “Materials” and “Fabric First” should not be compromised.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We suggest that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the Housing Standards Review and the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">potential </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">modifications to the Code for Sustainable Homes </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">must </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">give appropriate weight to the following:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of the “Materials” impacts identified in the Code.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of “Fabric First” and the “Fabric Energy Efficiency Standards” (FEES).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of Fabric First as a more reliable solution to long term energy and carbon savings in comparison to more complex “add on” heating solutions. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of long service life and low maintenance in the materials of construction.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of service life with respect to asset value and the acquisition of funding and insurance.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of Thermal Mass with respect to ventilation and the avoidance of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">over heating</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of indoor air quality and the maintenance of healthy homes.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of maintaining high levels of Responsible Sourcing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the supply chain of building materials</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of using materials which have the opportunity to be recycled/re used with minimum additional treatment.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The importance of developing and using harmonised systems for defining the environmental impacts of construction materials using Environmental Product Declarations (EPD) in accordance with BS EN 15804.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">20 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Declaration of interests.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wienerberger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> AG is the world’s largest producer of clay bricks and number 1 in clay roof tiles in Europe with 230 factories in 30 countries. Most of these are situated in EU Member States but some are outside the EU including the USA and India. The Group Head Office is based in Vienna.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wienerberger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Ltd in the UK – including the sister Company </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Sandtoft</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Roof Tiles Ltd – have a total of 14 manufacturing sites and a current workforce of around 1,000. Only 13 of these sites are currently operational.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> The Company manufactures clay facing and engineering bricks, clay pavers and roof tiles manufactured in clay, concrete and reconstituted slate.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>